clinic with a mark on his face which has started to itch recently. The mark has been present for many years and has not started to bother him until the itching occurred. He is otherwise in good health. The mark is readily visible (see Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Shave biopsy","Punch biopsy","Imiquimod cream","Excision with sentinel node biopsy","Local excision with 1-3 mm margin"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis lesion is clinically consistent with melanoma. Given the age of the patient and long history, this is likely consistent with lentigo maligna (previously known as Hutchinson\u0027s melanotic freckle). These lesions can remain dormant for years, but the recent development of new symptoms (itching) and the appearance of patchy increased pigmentation indicates malignant transformation, and as such, the lesion will require excision. \u003Cstrong\u003ELocal excision\u003C/strong\u003E of melanotic lesions should be complete with a 1-3 mm margin to allow use of sentinel lymph node biopsy if necessary following confirmation of the diagnosis. Surgical margin \u0026gt;3mm, may compromise the accuracy of sentinel lymph node biopsy and hence a 2mm is utilised. In large head and neck lesions an incisional biopsy, including punch or shave biopsies, may be a more practical initial approach. However, these would need to be multiple biopsies to minimise the chances of underestimating the diagnosis of lentigo maligna. In this particular case the size and position of the lesion should allow its complete excision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurther \u003Cstrong\u003Eexcision and sentinel lymph node biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E will depend on the depth of the tumour and the histological changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn argument could be made for a \u003Cstrong\u003Epunch biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E to establish the diagnosis. However, a punch biopsy does not represent the entire lesion and hence room for incorrect diagnosis and underestimate of the Breslow thickness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eshave biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E might be acceptable when the index of suspicion of malignant change is low - but that is not the case here, where is a high chance of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImiquimod cream\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to treat lentigo maligna where surgical option is contra-indicated. However, a biopsy to confirm the diagnosis should be done prior.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Suspected malignant melanocytic lesions should be locally excised with a 1-3mm margin","Sentinel lymph node biopsys provide no survival benefit to patients with suspected malignant melanomas"],"references":["Swetter SM, Tsao H, Bichakjian CK, Curiel-Lewandrowski C, Elder DE, Gershenwald JE, Guild V, Grant-Kels JM, Halpern AC, Johnson TM, Sober AJ. Guidelines of care for the management of primary cutaneous melanoma. Journal of the American Academy of Dermatology. 2019 Jan 1;80(1):208-50.","Dixon A, Anderson S, Steinman H, Nirenberg A, Dixon J. Sentinel lymph node biopsy now has a limited role in melanoma management. Australian family physician. 2014 Jul;43(7):479-80.","Ungureanu L, Vasilovici AF, Trufin II, et al. Lentigo Maligna Treatment\u2014An Update. J Clin Med. 2024; 13:2527.  doi: 10.3390/jcm13092527."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88225"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"350"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1710"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1710"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4605df17-8eaf-48a2-b52e-cd9ec0137d3a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4605df17-8eaf-48a2